d":"Durham, England, United Kingdom","Hesleden, Durham, England":"Hesleden, Durham, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hesilden","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Hazeldine  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hazeldine","meanings":["English: locative name, chiefly from Heselden (in Halton Gill, Durham), though Haselden (Sussex), Haslingden (Lancs), and Hazledon Farm (Wilts, recorded as  <i>Heseldene</i> in about 1130) are alternative possibilities. There has been some confusion with  <i>Hazelton</i>."]}]},{"name":"or","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name from <i>mór</i> ‘large, great’. This was the commonest of all girls’ names in late medieval Ireland, and has continued in use in both Ireland and Scotland to the present day."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Jueta","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Jewett  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Jewett","meanings":["English (northern): from the Middle English female personal name <i>Jouet</i>, <i>Jouot</i>, <i>Juet</i>. This was an Anglo-Norman French pronunciation of the Biblical name <i>Judith</i> and also a pet form (with the Anglo-Norman French suffix <i>-et(te)</i>) of both <i>Judith</i> and the much commoner female name <i>Julian</i> (from Latin <i>Juliana</i>, a derivative of <i>Julius</i>). See   Jew   and   Julian  .","Americanized form of French <b>Jouet</b> or <b>Jouët</b> (see   Jouett  ) and possibly also of some other similar (like-sounding) French surname.","History: This surname is listed along with the variant <i>Jouett</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":68,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":77,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":112,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Iueta or Jueta de Hesilden was born about 1147, in Durham, Durham, England as the daughter of Hesilden. She married Robert Hesilden about 1170, in Durham, Durham, England. They were the parents of at least 3 daughters."},"et":{"Abt 1147–":"umbes 1147–Surnud","1147–Female":"1147–Surnud","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1172–Female":"1172–Surnud","1178–Female":"1178–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1130":"1130","Abt 1147":"umbes 1147","1172":"1172","1160":"1160","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","Abt 1172":"umbes 1172","1224":"1224","1147":"1147","Abt 1178":"umbes 1178","1178":"1178","Abt 1160":"umbes 1160","Abt 1170":"umbes 1170","of Hesledene,Durham,England":"Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hesleden, Durham, England":"Hesleden, Durham, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1147–":"noin 1147–Kuollut","1147–Female":"1147–Kuollut","1130–Male":"1130–Kuollut","1160–Female":"1160–Kuollut","1172–Female":"1172–Kuollut","1178–Female":"1178–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1130":"1130","Abt 1147":"noin 1147","1172":"1172","1160":"1160","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","Abt 1172":"noin 1172","1224":"1224","1147":"1147","Abt 1178":"noin 1178","1178":"1178","Abt 1160":"noin 1160","Abt 1170":"noin 1170","of Hesledene,Durham,England":"Durham, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Hesleden, Durham, England":"Hesleden, Durham, England"},"fr":{"Abt 1147–":